[
    {
        "content": "<p>I was wondering if anyone had an example of a universal property which: 0) involves only very basic mathematics (stuff taught early courses in uni like groups, rings, metric spaces or vector spaces), 1) is not a (co)limit, 2) arises as a terminal object in a comma category, 3) does not involve a forgetful functor.</p>\n<p>I am giving a lecture on universal properties next week (after having taught (co)limits) and I am building a list of other kinds of universal properties. I have already developed the constructions of the free monoid generated by a set, the abelianization of a group and a basis of a vector space (equivalently, the free vector space). However, these all arise as initial objects in a comma category involving a forgetful functor into Set. Hence, I am looking for something a bit different. Last time I taught this class, I showed them how the evaluation function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>A</mi><mi>X</mi></msup><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A^X \\times X \\rightarrow A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.924661em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> was a universal morphism, but it did not seem to click with my students. Any ideas?</p>",
        "id": 213655076,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1602945677
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you're willing to forgive that the inclusion of the integers into the reals is actually a forgetful functor, one of my favourite examples is the adjoint triple given by (ceiling <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> floor).</p>",
        "id": 213666933,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602962740
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another good example is a natural numbers object. Every first year mathematics student learns how useful induction is, but most of the time, they don't realise that this is just a special case of recursion, which is much much more fundamental.</p>",
        "id": 213667392,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602963394
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A nice exercise, after defining what a natural numbers object is, is proving that taking the product with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">N</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{N}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">N</span></span></span></span></span> gives a right adjoint to the inclusion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">↺</mo></msup><mo>↪</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathscr{C}^{\\circlearrowleft} \\hookrightarrow \\mathscr{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.781386em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.1689em;\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.770386em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel amsrm mtight\">↺</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.1689em;\">C</span></span></span></span></span> (where the domain is the category of endomorphisms in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathscr{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.1689em;\">C</span></span></span></span></span>).</p>",
        "id": 213667754,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602963958
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Since Ralph seems to be teaching an introductory class, I hasten to add that you can define the universal property of the natural numbers in the category Set without getting into anything \"fancy\".</p>",
        "id": 213671150,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1602969444
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, beyond the category of sets, the next most accessible examples are some simple presheaf categories (e.g. endomaps of sets, sets through discrete time, graphs, etc...)</p>",
        "id": 213671740,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602970409
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Fawzi, I will think a bit more about this adjoint triple, but we have already covered the natural numbers as an initial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn mathvariant=\"bold\">1</mn><mo>+</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(\\mathbf{1}+-)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">1</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>--algebra. (We are doing natural transformations in the lecture after that, so I cannot discuss functor categories yet.)</p>",
        "id": 213671863,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1602970566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What about the extended natural numbers as a final <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">(1 + -)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> coalgebra?</p>",
        "id": 213671900,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Doel",
        "timestamp": 1602970670
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The reason I like adjoint triples as examples is that you see the contrast between the left and right adjoints</p>",
        "id": 213671952,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602970727
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another nice adjoint string is (connected components <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> discrete <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> points <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> codiscrete)</p>",
        "id": 213672115,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602971005
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Either with topological spaces over sets, or something more combinatorial</p>",
        "id": 213672117,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1602971029
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"284005\">Ralph Sarkis</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Example.20of.20universal.20property/near/213655076\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I was wondering if anyone had an example of a universal property which: 1) is not a (co)limit, 2) arises as a terminal object in a comma category</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Umm... Aren't these contradictory requirements?</p>",
        "id": 213698324,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1603013903
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"284005\">Ralph Sarkis</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Example.20of.20universal.20property/near/213671863\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>(We are doing natural transformations in the lecture after that, so I cannot discuss functor categories yet.)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>As a bridging example which you should be able to present even before presenting functor categories in full is a category of the form <span class=\"tex-error\">$$[M^{\\mathrm{op},\\mathbf{Set}]$$</span> of right actions of a monoid <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>; you can drop the op and use left actions if you prefer, or even use a group if you insist. The forgetful functor has left and right adjoints, but since you're looking for non-forgetful things, there is another adjoint triple whose middle functor is the functor from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68611em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span></span></span></span></span> sending a set to the trivial action of the monoid on that set: this is the global sections geometric morphism, if that means anything to you <span aria-label=\"wink\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f609\" role=\"img\" title=\"wink\">:wink:</span></p>",
        "id": 213698458,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1603014125
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">[Mod] Morgan Rogers</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Example.20of.20universal.20property/near/213698324\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Umm... Aren't these contradictory requirements?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Indeed, I meant not a (co)limit in the base category.</p>",
        "id": 213700207,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1603016912
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, I'll look into this triple as well.</p>",
